    front: "What is the Caparo three-part test for establishing a duty of care in negligence?",
    back: "The claimant must show: (1) the damage was foreseeable; (2) there was sufficient proximity between the parties; (3) it is fair, just and reasonable to impose a duty. All three limbs must be satisfied (Caparo Industries plc v Dickman [1990] 2 AC 605).",
    details: "Caparo replaced the Anns two-stage test and remains the leading authority. Courts use it incrementally — new duty situations are recognised only by analogy with established categories. In Caparo itself the House of Lords held auditors owed no duty to individual shareholders when they relied on accounts to buy shares, because proximity and fairness were absent. The test is particularly relevant in cases involving pure economic loss and negligent misstatement.",
