    front: "How does the law determine whether a defendant has breached the standard of care in negligence?",
    back: "The defendant is measured against the 'reasonable person' — an objective standard. The court weighs (i) probability of harm, (ii) potential severity, (iii) cost of precautions, and (iv) social utility of the activity. A small risk with disproportionate precaution cost may not constitute breach (Bolton v Stone [1951]).",
    details: "In Bolton v Stone a cricket ball hit a pedestrian; the House of Lords held no breach because the risk was foreseeable but very low, and the cost of eliminating it entirely was unreasonably high. Contrast Paris v Stepney Borough Council [1951] where the known vulnerability of a one-eyed employee elevated the standard — the employer was liable for not providing goggles. The standard is fixed (not personalised), but context adjusts the outcome: professionals are judged against the reasonable professional in their field (Bolam v Friern [1957]).",
