    crossCutting: false,
    front: "What test for remoteness of damage was established in The Wagon Mound (No 1) [1961]?",
    back: "A defendant is only liable for damage of a type that was reasonably foreseeable at the time of the negligent act. The precise manner of occurrence need not be foreseeable, but the kind of damage must be. Unforeseeable damage, however direct, is too remote.",
    details: "The Privy Council overruled the directness test from Re Polemis [1921]. Oil spilled from a ship ignited cotton waste in Sydney Harbour and burnt the plaintiff's wharf. The defendants were not liable because fire damage from oil floating on water was not reasonably foreseeable (only oil fouling was foreseeable). The 'type of damage' test has nuance: the 'thin skull' (eggshell skull) rule provides that once a type of damage is foreseeable, the defendant takes the victim as they find them, so an unforeseeably severe reaction does not break causation (Smith v Leech Brain [1962]).",
