    back: "A primary victim is directly imperilled or in the zone of physical danger (Page v Smith [1996] — foreseeability of physical injury suffices). A secondary victim witnesses injury to another and must satisfy four Alcock control mechanisms: (i) close tie of love and affection to the primary victim; (ii) proximity in time and space; (iii) perception with own unaided senses; (iv) medically recognised psychiatric illness.",
    details: "Page v Smith: claimant in a minor car accident suffered no physical injury but experienced chronic fatigue syndrome. HL held that because physical injury to him was foreseeable, psychiatric injury was actionable without the need for foreseeability of psychiatric harm specifically. Alcock v Chief Constable of South Yorkshire [1992] arose from Hillsborough: relatives watching on TV or who arrived after the disaster failed all control mechanisms. The distinction is critical — primary victims face fewer hurdles. White v Chief Constable of South Yorkshire [1999] held that police officers at Hillsborough were secondary victims (not primary) because they were not in personal danger.",
