    front: "State the rule in Rylands v Fletcher and its requirements.",
    back: "A person who for their own purposes brings onto their land something likely to do mischief if it escapes must keep it at their peril. If they fail to do so they are prima facie answerable for all the direct consequences of its escape (Blackburn J, confirmed HL 1868). Requirements: accumulation, non-natural use of land, escape, and foreseeable damage.",
    details: "The defendant in Rylands v Fletcher built a reservoir; contractors negligently failed to block old mine shafts; water flooded the plaintiff's mine. The House of Lords added 'non-natural use' as a qualifying element. Cambridge Water Co v Eastern Counties Leather [1994] confirmed the requirement of foreseeability of damage of the relevant type. The tort is essentially dormant in England & Wales after Transco v Stockport MBC [2003], where the House of Lords declined to abolish it but significantly restricted 'non-natural use' — ordinary domestic or commercial use of land does not qualify.",
