    tags: ["vicarious liability", "course of employment", "employer", "frolic"],
    crossCutting: false,
    front: "When is an employer vicariously liable for the torts of an employee?",
    back: "An employer is vicariously liable for an employee's tort if (1) an employment relationship (or akin to employment) exists, and (2) the tort was committed in the course of employment — meaning there is a sufficient close connection between the employment and the wrongful act (Lister v Hesley Hall [2001]; Various Claimants v Catholic Child Welfare Society [2012]).",
    details: "The old 'Salmond test' asked whether the act was authorised or a wrongful mode of a lawful act. The close connection test, developed for intentional wrongdoing (sexual abuse by a warden), is now the main approach. Frolic of one's own (going completely off piste for personal purposes) breaks the employment connection — but a detour for mixed purposes may not (Rose v Plenty [1976]: milkman letting a child on his float was still acting in course of employment). The two-stage test in Various Claimants includes: (i) does the relationship make it just to impose liability, and (ii) is there a sufficient connection between the relationship and the tort?",
