    back: "Nemo dat quod non habet — no one can transfer better title than they have (s21 SGA 1979). Exceptions: (1) estoppel (s21(1)); (2) sale by mercantile agent (Factors Act 1889 s2); (3) sale under voidable title (s23); (4) sale by seller in possession after sale (s24); (5) sale by buyer in possession (s25); (6) sale under court order.",
    details: "The rule protects original owners but exceptions protect bona fide purchasers for value. S23: if the original sale was voidable (e.g. for fraudulent misrepresentation) and the rogue re-sells before the contract is avoided, a bona fide purchaser gets good title (Ingram v Little [1961] contrast with Lewis v Averay [1972]). S25 buyer in possession: the buyer who has received delivery can pass good title to a bona fide third party (Newtons of Wembley v Williams [1965]). The Factors Act s2 protects purchasers who buy from a mercantile agent acting with the owner's consent and in the ordinary course of business.",
