    back: "A seller may retain legal title in goods until the purchase price is paid (s19 SGA 1979 allows reservation of title). Where goods are identifiable and unmixed, an effective Romalpa clause allows the seller to recover them in the buyer's insolvency, ranking ahead of unsecured creditors.",
    details: "The full 'Romalpa clause' in the case also claimed proceeds of sub-sales held on trust — a claim that later courts restricted. Simple retention of title (title remains until paid) is routinely upheld. Extended clauses claiming products after mixing or sub-sale proceeds have generally failed: Borden (UK) v Scottish Timber [1981] — resin mixed into chipboard lost identity; Re Peachdart [1984] — leather made into handbags converted the goods. In practice, simple clauses are commonplace in commercial supply contracts as a credit protection device.",
