    front: "What are the three functions of a bill of lading?",
    back: "A bill of lading is: (1) a receipt for goods shipped, acknowledging the condition and quantity of goods on loading; (2) evidence of (or the actual) contract of carriage between shipper and carrier; (3) a document of title — endorsement and delivery transfers constructive possession and, under the Carriage of Goods by Sea Act 1992, contractual rights.",
    details: "As a document of title, only a negotiable (order) bill transfers property when endorsed in blank or to order — making it essential in CIF and FOB international sale contracts where goods are sold 'afloat'. The Carriage of Goods by Sea Act 1992 replaced the Bills of Lading Act 1855 and transfers contractual rights to a lawful holder who becomes the holder by endorsement. A sea waybill is not a document of title and is used for non-negotiable consignments. The Hague-Visby Rules (Carriage of Goods by Sea Act 1971) imply minimum carrier obligations and limit liability.",
