    crossCutting: false,
    front: "What are the four requirements for a right to be capable of being an easement, as set out in Re Ellenborough Park [1956]?",
    back: "Re Ellenborough Park (CA) held an easement must: (1) there must be a dominant and servient tenement; (2) an easement must accommodate and serve the dominant tenement; (3) the dominant and servient owners must be different persons; (4) the right must be capable of forming the subject matter of a grant (i.e. it must be definable and exercisable by a grantee).",
    details: "The case concerned a right to use a communal garden: the CA upheld it as an easement satisfying all four tests. The 'accommodate and serve' test requires a nexus between the right and the use of the dominant land — a right that merely benefits the owner personally does not qualify (Hill v Tupper [1863]: right to put boats on canal was too personal). The fourth requirement excludes vague rights ('right to a view') and rights that would amount to exclusive possession. Easements can be legal or equitable and are acquired by express/implied grant or prescription (20 years' user).",
