  front: "How can the terms of a trust be varied?",
  back: "Three main routes: (1) Saunders v Vautier (1841): if all beneficiaries are adult, of full capacity, and together absolutely entitled, they can direct the trustees to end the trust or vary its terms. (2) Variation of Trusts Act 1958: the court can approve an arrangement varying the trust on behalf of persons who cannot consent (minors, unborn, unascertained, or those with mere contingent interests) — the court must be satisfied the arrangement is for the benefit of those on whose behalf it approves. (3) Inherent jurisdiction: the court can authorise specific acts (e.g. emergency investment powers).",
  details: "Under the VTA 1958, 'benefit' includes financial benefit and non-financial benefit (e.g. family harmony — Re Weston's Settlements [1969], though the court refused to approve a variation designed solely for tax avoidance by moving to Jersey). The arrangement must be genuine and not merely a revocation and resettlement (Re Ball's Settlement [1968]). S.57 Trustee Act 1925 allows the court to authorise specific transactions not permitted by the trust instrument.",
